Flock Safety takes billions of photos every month spying on millions of innocent Americans. Their work raises Fourth Amendment concerns by enabling broad, warrantless surveillance of law-abiding citizens, normalizing continuous government tracking. Privacy advocates warn that centralizing massive amounts of location data creates serious security vulnerabilities, making it a high-value target for breaches, misuse, or unauthorized access. “Spying” can be defined as the systematic monitoring, collection, and analysis of individuals’ movements or activities without their knowledge or meaningful consent.

